## Results and discussion:

For the cavity at 45\({}^{\circ}\) angle, the polariton peaks were of equal intensity in the transmission spectrum. Theoretical calculations predicted an ultrafast non-radiative decay of the upper polariton branch into the exciton reservoir in a time of about 50 fs and another non-radiative scattering from the exciton reservoir to the lower polariton branch in around 9-350 ps [4]. The amplitude of the pump-induced differential absorption of the exciton reservoir, upper and lower polariton branches was modeled for polariton population based on this theoretical calculation to give decay times of 150 fs and 3.2 ps respectively. A high frequency modulation of the polariton and exciton reservoir population was taken as due to the excitation of intermolecular phonons generated due to these two non-radiative processes. However the Rabi oscillation between the two polariton states could not be easily distinguished. This could be due the overlap of positive and negative signals in the differential transmission through the cavity corresponding to the ground-state bleaching and the excited state absorption. By passing just a single pulse through the cavity in the time-resolved up-conversion technique multiple transitions are avoided and clear oscillations are visible.

The up-conversion of the just the two pulses gave a single pulse spectrum which is the result of cross-correlation of two short pulses. However the transmission through the cavity time-resolved at 0\({}^{\circ}\), 20\({}^{\circ}\) and 30\({}^{\circ}\) angles of incidence show oscillation of 35 fs time period which correspond to Rabi oscillation of the lower polariton branch population. This is supported by the fact that 35 fs corresponds to a Rabi splitting of 120meV at resonance which is observed in the transmission/ reflection spectra through the cavity. Two simultaneous oscillations in the UV, out-of-phase with each other, corresponding to the expected Rabi-splitting at the exciton resonance for the cavity at 40\({}^{\circ}\) were observed. All these oscillations are additionally enveloped by a longer single-exponential decay of time of around 70 fs which is the photon lifetime of the cavity mode.

## Conclusion:

Polariton relaxation dynamics were observed using pump-probe spectroscopy and were found to be in agreement with previously calculated values. Coherent exchange of energy between cavity polariton states in ultrafast time scale was observed in a J-aggregate semiconductor microcavity directly, without any need for data processing, using time-resolved up-conversion technique and once again in agreement with expected values.

